'''Pakistanis in Russia''' are a fairly small community; in 2004, there were up to 2,000 expatriates, with almost all belonging to the [[Pashtuns|Pashtun]] ethnic group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opf.org.pk/download/anual/YEARBK.pdf|title=Overseas Pakistanis Foundation: 2004-2005 Yearbook|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524170403/http://www.opf.org.pk/download/anual/YEARBK.pdf|archivedate=24 May 2010|df=}}</ref> A significant number of individuals are international students undergoing medicine in various universities and colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sasnet.lu.se/panelabstracts/25.html|title=South Asians in Russia: A New Element in the Multicultural Mosaic|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622032712/http://www.sasnet.lu.se/panelabstracts/25.html|archivedate=22 June 2011|df=}}</ref> Most Pakistanis are concentrated around large cities, including the capital [[Moscow]]. The community has established a Pakistani [[mosque]] in [[Saint Petersburg Polytechnical University|St. Petersburg Polytechnic]]. 
There is also a Pakistan Study Centre which operates in the [[Russian State Library]], founded by the embassy and local community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakistantimes.net/pt/detail.php?newsId=9775|title=Pakistan Study Centre opens in Moscow: Pakistan Times|publisher=|accessdate=24 November 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313004336/http://pakistantimes.net/pt/detail.php?newsId=9775|archivedate=13 March 2012|df=}}</ref>
Moreover, [[University of Punjab]] has signed an agreement with Moscow State University in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakru.ru/|title=pakru.ru domain has expired|website=pakru.ru|accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref>

